  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3212187783" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3212187783" />
    <a title="Ivana Books Are Magic" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/56173179-ivana-books-are-magic"><img alt="Ivana Books Are Magic" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1578249636p2/56173179.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3212187783?book_show_action=true">Mar 02, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ivana Books Are Magic" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ivana Books Are Magic" href="/user/show/56173179-ivana-books-are-magic">Ivana Books Are Magic</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780061578939" href="/book/show/2817201-brida">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3212187783" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11946716941996779204">Brida is Special. We know this because Paulo Coelho uses a lot of capital letters when describing her Life. It is because of all the capital letters that we know that she is really on a Path. Don&apos;t question the Path, for it is written with a capital letter. It doesn&apos;t have to make any sense. There doesn&apos;t have to be a plot of any kind. Spiritual sounding quotes will do and if that isn&apos;t enough, thrown in an attractive young woman and descriptions of nature. That will do. Brida has a Gift. We kno</span>
  <span id="freeText11946716941996779204" style="display:none">Brida is Special. We know this because Paulo Coelho uses a lot of capital letters when describing her Life. It is because of all the capital letters that we know that she is really on a Path. Don't question the Path, for it is written with a capital letter. It doesn't have to make any sense. There doesn't have to be a plot of any kind. Spiritual sounding quotes will do and if that isn't enough, thrown in an attractive young woman and descriptions of nature. That will do. Brida has a Gift. We know this because her ears are small- a sure sign of those who posses the Gift, a sign that will enable her to become a student of powerful wizards and witches. If you want them to accept them in your little club and you happen to have big ears, I guess it is off to the plastic surgeon. <br /><br />Anyhow, Brida is on an important Spiritual Journey. She is not like us mere mortals because she has lived many times. She is reborn over and over again so she can do what? Help others join her on her path that consists of exactly what? Congratulating themselves how cool they are because they are capable of magic? Becoming teachers to others so they can do bunch of rituals and do what? Use magic? Recognize their Other Half and make love to them? But then supposedly even mechanics use magic without knowing. I guess Brida is more cool because she will use it knowingly. <br /><br />At some point, Brida finds a teacher and then does tons of rituals and that means she is opening herself to Magic. So, Brida can finally feel she's better than others and special. Good for her. What do we really know about her? I suppose it doesn't matter. What is her character development? What? That's not important, for there are capital letters instead of that. Brida is young, a bit insecure and presumably attractive, a character that should appeal to a wider audience. Brida has a beautiful body. All bodies are beautiful the author will inform us, but will also imply that Brida's is Beautiful. A bit of a cliche isn't it? A beautiful young woman choosing between two men? <br /><br />What is Brida's great realization? Wicca, her spiritual teacher/witch tells her that it is about admitting that we don't know anything. That's the meaning of life supposedly. But many times in the book it is stressed that the meaning of life is to find our Other Half. Apparently we all have this Half and we need to find it in any incarnation. This idea didn't really appeal to me. I guess I'm not a romantic. This whole idea about finding our Other Half no matter what sounds childish to me. It means we don't have a choice. I don't mind the reincarnation theory, but what does this book really offers than a cheesy love triangle and a bunch of spiritual sounding quotes? If we have a choice and free will then we can destroy our soul and the soul of our Other Half as well. The whole idea of a free choice is that you can destroy yourself. What about becoming our Other Half instead of searching for what we lack in others? This whole fantasy of it all turning out well in the end because it is predestined seems juvenile to me. More often than not, life doesn't turn out well. Who is to say that the after life is any better? <br /><br />In all fairness, Brida wasn't a terrible book. Some parts of it were kind of interesting. There were some lovely descriptions and messages. I didn't hated it, but Brida was definitely predictable. The more I read of this author, the more predictable he becomes. His novels are something like spiritual fast food. They may look good at first glance but there isn't much substance in them. There are no interesting moral dilemmas or theological questions. What you get is a lot of memorable and inspiring quotes taken from various traditions and from author himself. Coelho never goes into depth. For example, take the characters. What do we really know about them? We learn a bit about their background. At some point, Brida's mother appeals to tell an inspiring story but she soon vanishes. It all sounds too idyllic. There isn't much of plot either. All must work out because Coelho must be a Bestseller. That is the Destiny. I have a feeling that it is all left unfinished so it can sound deep and meaningful. I suppose I'm just getting tired of Coelho superficial spiritual new age stuff. I'm sure there are people who will be inspired by this book. I don't blame them. There are some nice and imaginative passages in it. However, I wasn't particularly inspired by it and there's that. I've had enough of Coelho.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11946716941996779204" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


